<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-10-18T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-10-18T07:00:00-05:00" n="46" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d46">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">467n.11/11: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Jerusalem</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Knabenshue</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Jerusalem</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-10-18T14:00:00+02:00">October 18, 1929—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 18—9:45 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Inasmuch as the local law does not seem to afford adequate damages for
                            injuries and loss of life suffered during the recent disturbances <pb facs="0179" n="61" xml:id="pg_61"/> and since the character of the
                            disturbances and other elements involved therein might justify
                            international claims, will the Department please instruct me by
                            telegraph whether I should make reservations in this respect to the
                            Palestine Government before the expiration of the 2 months’ limit?</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Knabenshue</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>